      <title>General Reflection - Preview</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here is a schematic sketch of a reflection of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> about a hyperspace <math>
                     <latex>H</latex>
                  </math>, parallel to a vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math> complementary to <math>
                     <latex>H</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/ReflectionParallelToVector.png"/>
            </media>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here the vectors <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math> are being reflected about the hyperspace <math>
                     <latex>H</latex>
                  </math>, parallel to the vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>
                  </math>. The result of this projection are the vectors <math>
                     <latex>R(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>R(\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>H</latex>
                  </math>, respectively. â€“ Note that, contrary to orthogonal reflections, general reflections need not be length preserving.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
